# Ultra-hard tier tasks — 8 tasks — require deep CS knowledge, multi-file, 100-200 steps
# Format: task_name|prompt

raft-consensus|Work in /tmp/training-raft/. Init go mod (go mod init training/raft). Implement a simplified single-node Raft in raft.go (package main): RaftNode with state (Follower/Candidate/Leader), log []LogEntry, commitIndex, currentTerm, votedFor. Methods: AppendEntries(term int, entries []LogEntry) bool, RequestVote(term int, candidateID int) bool, Propose(cmd string) (index int, err error), stepDown(). Write raft_test.go testing: leader election (single node elects itself), log appending, term increments, stale term rejection. Run go test ./... Acceptance: all tests pass, no data races.
b-tree|Work in /tmp/training-btree/. Init go mod (go mod init training/btree). Implement a B-tree of order T (min degree) in btree.go (package main): NewBTree(t int) *BTree, Insert(key int), Search(key int) bool, Delete(key int), InOrder() []int. Handle node splitting on insert and merging/redistribution on delete. Write btree_test.go with sequential insert 1-1000 and verify InOrder returns sorted, random deletion test leaving tree valid, and edge cases (delete nonexistent, single key). Run go test ./... Acceptance: InOrder always sorted, all invariants maintained.
lock-free-queue|Work in /tmp/training-lfqueue/. Init go mod (go mod init training/lfqueue). Implement a lock-free concurrent MPMC queue in queue.go using sync/atomic and unsafe.Pointer (Michael-Scott queue algorithm): NewQueue[T any]() *Queue[T], Enqueue(v T), Dequeue() (T, bool). Write queue_test.go with a stress test: 8 producers and 8 consumers, 100000 total items, verify no items lost or duplicated using atomic counters. Run go test -race ./... Acceptance: race detector clean (atomic ops only), no lost items.
persistent-trie|Work in /tmp/training-ptrie/. Init go mod (go mod init training/ptrie). Implement a persistent (copy-on-write) trie in ptrie.go: Insert(root *Node, word string) *Node returns new root without modifying old, Search(root *Node, word string) bool. Each version is immutable. Write ptrie_test.go verifying that inserting into v1 produces v2, v1 still has original words, v2 has both. Test with 1000 random words across 50 versions. Run go test ./... Acceptance: all versions independently correct.
wal|Work in /tmp/training-wal/. Init go mod (go mod init training/wal). Implement a Write-Ahead Log in wal.go (package main): NewWAL(path string) (*WAL, error), Append(entry []byte) (lsn uint64, err error), ReadFrom(lsn uint64) ([][]byte, error), Sync() error, Close() error. Each record: 8-byte LSN + 4-byte length + payload + 4-byte CRC32 checksum. Detect and reject corrupted records on read. Write wal_test.go: append 10000 entries, crash-simulate by truncating file mid-record, verify ReadFrom stops at corruption and returns valid entries only. Run go test ./... Acceptance: CRC corruption detected, no panic.
regex-engine|Work in /tmp/training-regex/. Init go mod (go mod init training/regex). Implement a regex engine in regex.go supporting: literal chars, . (any char), * (zero or more), + (one or more), ? (optional), | (alternation), () (grouping), ^ and $ anchors. Use Thompson NFA construction. API: Compile(pattern string) (*Regexp, error), Match(s string) bool. Write regex_test.go with tests covering all operators, anchors, alternation, nested groups, and edge cases (empty pattern, empty string). Do NOT use regexp stdlib. Run go test ./... Acceptance: all tests pass.
memory-allocator|Work in /tmp/training-alloc/. Init go mod (go mod init training/alloc). Implement a slab allocator in alloc.go (package main): NewAllocator(slabSizes []int) *Allocator where slabSizes are power-of-2 slab sizes (e.g. 8,16,32,64,128,256). Alloc(size int) []byte returns a slab from the appropriate free list or allocates a new one. Free(b []byte) returns slab to the free list. Large allocs (>max slab) fall through to make(). Write alloc_test.go verifying: correct slab selection, free list reuse (Alloc+Free+Alloc returns same backing array), concurrent alloc/free with -race. Run go test -race ./... Acceptance: race clean, free list reuse verified.
jit-vm|Work in /tmp/training-jit/. Init go mod (go mod init training/jit). Implement a bytecode VM with JIT-style optimization in vm.go (package main). Bytecode ops: PUSH int64, POP, ADD, SUB, MUL, DIV, HALT. VM has a stack and executes bytecode. Add a peephole optimizer that runs before execution: fold constant expressions (PUSH a, PUSH b, ADD -> PUSH (a+b)), eliminate dead pops (PUSH x, POP -> nothing). API: NewVM() *VM, Load(ops []Op), Optimize() []Op, Run() (int64, error). Write vm_test.go testing execution correctness and that optimizer reduces instruction count for constant expressions. Run go test ./... Acceptance: optimizer reduces instructions, results identical pre/post optimize.
